\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid5701797 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Could I have your name please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Robert Bracken.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 100 Robert Hall Street, Salford 5.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And you're single?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 12}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  March 1902.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your birthplace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 14 New Cambridge Street, Salford 5.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How many years did you live in the house you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 About 16 years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Where did you move to then? Where did you live after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Here. 100 Robert Hall Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And you've lived here until the present day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember why the family made the first move? From Cambridge Street to Robert Hall Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Probably a bigger house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Four sisters, and only myself brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And can you tell me their birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The first one was 1888, 1890, 1897, 1900 and I came in 1902.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 He would have been thirty six years of age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me where he came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Manchester.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 He was a railway goods checker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he have another job before he became that or did he have one afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No, not as far as I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he do any casual or part-time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he have this job until he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No I don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 About thirty seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Manchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And did she have any jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 She worked in a printing works.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did she work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. She stayed at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did she have any part-time jobs ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 None at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me the hours approximately that she did in this printing job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 From about eight o'clock in the morning until about half past five in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 She didn't do any jobs at all after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I should like to ask you now about life at home when you were a child; the time up to when you left school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How many rooms were there in the house in New Cambridge Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 There would be four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me how many reception rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 A living room and a kitchen and two bedrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No relatives or lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No lodgers, no relatives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No she did it all herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was the washing done at home or sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Washing done at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your mother did it all, did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother or father mend or make the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Mother did occasionally make clothes for the girls. Dresses, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were the clothes new or were they sometimes secondhand? You know, often they were passed down weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. But mostly new.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Where were they bought? Were they bought at local shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Local shops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me when? Was there any special occasion when they were bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Probably whit week, when we say had our best clothes for walking, walking in the procession. Or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 E}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 aster time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now what about shoes, did your father or mother mend the family's shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. We bought them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were they new or secondhand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 New.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me where they were bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Local shops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Usually when we needed them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house? Did he do any cleaning at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Not ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Cooking, was he a good cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 He never bothered to cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he light the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes he'd get the fires ready.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he do any decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. He'd always get a man to come in to decorate. A tradesman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about repairs in the house, or improvements to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he dress or undress you or bath you? Did he ever you\rquote re your mother with this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No my mother did it all herself, when we were young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes he did. And I used to watch him writing and got my writing from him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 He used to write as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well when he was writing his letters I used to discover how he wrote, because he was a beautiful hand-writer, and I copied him. But he did read to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember the type of stories at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh I don't know, but they were really not fairy tales.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he take you out without your mother at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes, we used to go out on a Sunday. Have a walk round on Sunday morning, come back in time for dinner, everything would be ready.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he take you to Church? I know you would go to Church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. We went to church with him, 'til we was bigger. Then we went ourselves, on our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he look after you when she was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No I don't remember whether he did or not. Of course my sisters were bigger then you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And they would look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you have any tasks you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No brothers, only myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How about your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes they'd help in the house. They'd do the cleaning up or shopping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How long did they continue to do these tasks? Did they do them until they left school or after they left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh right up 'til they got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And it was mostly cleaning and helping your mother about the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did the older sisters help the younger ones with things they found difficult, like dressing or eating, or did they look a
fter them in any other ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well I don't think so, they were mostly on par, their ages was near enough, they helped one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did the younger children help the older ones in anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No, I can't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your school days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well yes, we usually went about eight o'clock. If it was winter time, yes. But I think even in summer time. Always about eight o'clock.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 For the
 early years, yes. My mother took us to bed and then we had, before electric light or gas was in the bedroom, we had an old lamp, an oil lamp, a paraffin lamp, and then we'd get nicely in bed and she'd fold our arms then she'd say the prayers and then the
 light would go down gradually and then she would go out of the room quietly. That's when she put us to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 At what age did you start to put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh I should think about eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you share the bedroom or bed with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
I had my own bed but I shared the room. My mother and father were in the same room, but I was in the corner screened off. My sisters were in the other room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 In the kitchen, but later we went to the public baths.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Where were the public baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Regent Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were they open all the time at the public baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes, every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How much did they charge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think it was about tuppence, at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How often did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Went twice a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And when did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Every week and when we'd got them soiled. But mostly we dressed up for the weekend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now can you tell me where the family had their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 In the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were there any occasions when they ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No, we might go into the parlour, the front part of the house, for a family gathering.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Not for birthdays or Christmas or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We never celebrated birthdays much. We might get a card sometimes, rarely, a 
card. We might get a happy birthday and that was all. Say 'It's your birthday, today' but nothing further.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 In the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me what type of kitchen equipment she had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We had a gas stove but very
 often she'd cook on the kitchen fire - open range. And a large pan, potatoes and so on. Kept on the hob. I remember the iron kettle boiling away the water steaming up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 So she did part of it on the open range and part by gas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well we didn't have it altogether. Those who had to go out to work had it earlier. My sisters who worked in the mill had to be at work for six o'clock they'd probably get a cup of tea about half past five, because breakfast was eight
 o'clock then when they'd come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They always sat down at the table together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They always sat down at the table, and we got it about quarter past eight before we went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 So which sisters would have it first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The two eldest sisters who were working.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And the rest of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Would be together about quarter past eight.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What did you usually eat and drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well we had porridge, and egg, toast and tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you have anything different on certain days, Sundays for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Breakfast, no, we had just the same for Sunday. Nothing special.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about midday meals, what did you usually have for midday meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 During the week we'd have hot pot, potato pie - usually done in a brown dish and a
 nice thick crust put on the top, baked by my mother, or fish on Friday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about evening meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Evening meals might be potatoes, or a chop, nothing special.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother or father bake the bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 My mother did. She made her own 
bread. She would get a hundred weight of flour, 112-lbs. and made her own bread and cakes, to last all the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 She always got a hundred weight of flour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. That would last her. She'd delve into the flour, whatever she wanted to make the brea
d and what was left over she'd make cakes with the dough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 She never bought bread at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Very rarely. Very rarely indeed. It was always home-made.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about jam, did she make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Occasionally she made her own jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did she bottle fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. She'd bottle fruit - plums she'd bottle, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about vegetables? Did she ever bottle vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did she make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No she never made pickles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did she make any medicines for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No I can't remember her making any medicines.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was any beer brewed for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 She used to make beer. Home-made beer in a big yellow mug, and bottle that. And have nettles or whatever it was drying on the
 line. Drying on the line, nettles and herbs ready for her beer and sometimes she used to tell me before I was born she used to sell it on a Sunday morning to people who came knocking at the door. They loved it. That's when she lived in Manchester before 
they came up to Salford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother or father grow their own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did they buy any vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I can't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about tinned or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well tinned - there wa
sn't much going then - I don't think they were. I've never seen tins come into the house. I've never seen my mother open tins, the vegetables were all bought and cooked, but nothing was opened from a tin.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did they keep any livestock for the family; hens, pigs, goats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No, I don't remember ever any hens being kept.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think all the week, with the exception of Friday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Fresh meat was it, or tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Fresh meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Always had fresh meat? Never had tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Never tinned meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever get some extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No I think we all got served alike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your father have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes he might have got a little bit more. But we were always looked after ourselves. There was no such thing as big helpings or extra food for anybody.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes, we did talk, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Just as much as you wished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes went on talking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We had what was cooked. The main meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What was your parents' attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 My mother would say "You mustn't be hungry else you would have eat it." But we didn't have to eat it if we didn't want to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 If there was something on the table you wanted, like the 
salt, could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait until it was passed to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When it was close to we helped ourselves, but if it wasn't we might ask "Pass the salt.".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. Oh yes. Very often we did if we was hungry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit in a certain way at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh no. We were never allowed to do that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We could leave when we'd finished our own lunch. We never waited for anybody to finish theirs, we could leave almost at once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you always have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes we always sat at the same place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How was the meal served? Who served it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 My mother always served the meal. But on a Sunday my father used to cut the meat. He was the carver of the joint - usually a leg of
 mutton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Always a leg of mutton was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes, for about 2/6d. Rather a large leg too. And it could be sold by auction on a Saturday night and beat down a price from half a crown. And butchers opened 'til eleven and midnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 This was the local butcher was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
There was a group of butchers in a certain street, Tatton Street, and they were beating one another down. There'd be a lot left and there was no fridges, it would probably go bad and they used to auction the meat right up 'til elev
en, and people would come specially at that time to get cheap joints.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And did this apply in the fish market?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes they used to come out in the middle of the road and barter against one another. And mimic one another. And shouting kind of jokes
 to one another, and people were taking part in it all the time. Oh yes, that's true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And this was always late on a Saturday night, at the end of the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What time about on a Saturday night that the auctioning would start?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 About ten or eleven o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And it went on 'til when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 'Til they were sold out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you find a lot of people waited for this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Definitely. They came specially for the purpose. But very often we had ours bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Where did the younger brothers and sisters sit before they could feed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think I sat in the high chair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about the other brothers and sisters, did they have the high chair too, was it passed down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well I think it was passed down. You see I was the
 last. I think the chair would have been passed down. It was a very high chair and a bib put round your neck - anything dropping wouldn't go on your clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who used to feed you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 My mother always.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Very often we'd sit out sometimes at the
 front door in the high chair to get the fresh air because it was safer. We wouldn't run out into the traffic. We were there, fastened in, and we could see who was passing and take the air as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 At what age did you join the family at the table for meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Probably five or six years of age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. A very good person to talk to. Enlightened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did she show you affection at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. She would. But she had no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 favoritism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  for any of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 She was a warm hearted affectionate person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Full of it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 If you had any worries could you share them with her or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We would. We could go to her in difficulties and she'd help us out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was your father an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. We could get on well with him. But then again, as I said before, he was always busy writing, doing social work for other people. He belonged to the Church, and then there was a charitable organisation and he was the head, and people might be c
oming to see us any time. Probably girls going into the mill, at that time they wore a mill piney (apron) and they hadn't got one, couldn't afford to buy one, and they'd come to him to see what he could do, and he would very often help them out, or give t
h
em a ticket to go to a certain shop for clogs. They were clogs as they wore in them days. And he was always writing to people who was in the know to see if he could find jobs for these people. Introductory letters to different foremen on the docks or on t
h
e railway. And every Sunday when we had a high tea he used to say to my mother, "Clear the table because I want to get all my correspondence up, I may never know who comes." And the house was a rendezvous for people who wanted to interview him, that's tal
k to, so that he could help them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. And he did this through the Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
He did this through the Church and now and again people outside the Church got to know, such as the 'Cinderella' Society. The Cinderella Society, I think when I was quite 
young - my mother told me about it - where they sent so many leaves of bread to help out the poor in the district. They knew him because he was secretary of the Church Society.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And the Cinderella Society, was it attached to your Church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. It was attached by the, what we call the old Evening Chronicle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The Evening Chronicle ran it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
They had the Cinderella Club and they sent this bread, and my father used to have to take this bread to people who wouldn't come, because they had false pride. The house would be clean outside but there was poverty within.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you see much poverty around here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Oh yes. Plenty of poverty. Plenty of poverty indeed. Pawn shops with frequent access on a Monday morning. Six o'clock waiting outside. And
 people used to pawn their Sunday clothes. Take them off on a Sunday 'til the Friday and then get them redeemed. Oh if you didn't get them out on a Friday there'd be frequent rows 'cos they'd have no clothes for, what we'd call the Sunday clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who would the rows be with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
The men angry with their wives, because they hadn't got the clothes, they couldn't afford the money to get them. Money was scarce. Money was only small in those days, and pawn shops was a frequent source of revenue, if you like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 But of course it would be expensive this way because they would have to pay a small surcharge wouldn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well no, I think there was only about a 1/2d or 1d for the ticket. And if they got them hung up it was a 1d extra to hand them up. V
ery often they wasn't hung up at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 There was no charge for borrowing the money, just the ticket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
They'd lend so much money on the clothes and I'm told if you went somewhere else to pawn them, the pawn broker had a certain way of pinning
 them up, so the next pawn broker would know they had been somewhere else. But the pawn broker would say "Oh they're only worth so much this week, I can't give you any more", and he'd barter down 'til the poor should would have to take what she was offere
d.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well suppose they were offered 2/6d, when they went back, how much approximately would they have to pay to redeem them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They would have to pay the 2/6d, plus how long they had been in for the week. May be about 3/-.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 So it would be 6d charge and then ticket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes and hanging up, because if it was a dress or a suit it was hung up. And very often it wasn't hung up but they said it was hung up. And the person would say, "The clothes is creased they haven't been hung up and I paid yo
u for that". And there was nothing they could do about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your father show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 He was very good. My father was very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 If you had worries could you share them with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes you could. And my father and mother were good
, they never had any rows, not in front of us. Not in front of the children. They'd have their own differences when we went to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well of course we always respected my mother and father. 
And we always called them by their proper name 'Mother' and 'Father'. There was no such thing as 'the old girl' or the 'old fella', No. They were always respected by us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brother and sisters, or sisters in your case, in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Nothing special at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did they say you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well yes. We rarely got into any trouble or any scrapes, but we did hit back, if we could manage it, if they weren't too big.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be? Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes, they wanted us to be trained well. And there was no badness went into t
he house. Morals were good. There was no bad language or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They didn't like swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well it never entered into the home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What do you think they wanted you to be though, eventually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't know. There's nothing spe
cial in mind. My father had nothing special in mind, I was only twelve when he died, you see. I might have entered an office or something, but there was no vocations we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember what things they thought were right and what things they thought were wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
My mother had an horror of getting anything on credit or on tick. She'd pay her bills as she went along. And they were always keen on honesty and truth. To tell the truth to everybody and never overstep the mark to any neighbour or an
y child or anything like that, or school teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When grown-ups were talking, were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We never did join in. We were told not to join in.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 If you did something that your parents disapproved of, what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Very often kept in. Or remonstrated about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who did this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 My mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me how?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
She'd warn us. She'd lecture, she'd warn us, and say "That shouldn't be done or that shouldn't be said." And we'd probably stay in or keep from the danger where we'd been already in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 It was always your mother, never by anybody else, never by your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well no, because we'd be young then. When my father died I were only twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No I don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you feel about punishment whenever your mother did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I wasn't resentful. I thought well I deserved it. And it deterred me from doing any harm any more. That's all I can say about that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Would you say
 that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents, or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. I think my father until he died, then my mother, who I kind of idolised. We got all our mannerisms and habits a
nd tuition from her, 'cos she was good. She was ideal in the home. She was good. And well we never went wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your father did help as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes. Yes. Both.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't 
remember it ever being different. Only it was just our birthday. We were reminded it was our birthday. We might get a present but nothing spectacular. I don't think there was a party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you have anything special to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Never have guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. Very often the birthday would pass over and that's all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well on Christmas Day, Christmas Eve, the toys were bought, and they were slowly put 
into the room and we kind of sensed something was happening. We were fast asleep and now and again we would waken, and look what was there, but we'd never touch them 'til Christmas morning. And they just shared our happiness on Christmas morning with our 
toys. The evening, Christmas Eve, my parents had gone out to Church, Midnight Mass, we were well away, asleep, and they'd come and see as we were alright. But we had a good Christmas Day and they shared in our happiness with the toys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
No. We had a guest used to come to us now and again with a violin and play it and we had what we called our Sunday Evening performances, when the gathering was of aunts and relations would come. And the fiddler would 
be in the corner, and they'd all dance and drink in between, and move the table, and all the crockery off the table, and dance in the middle of the floor. And that was their enjoyment. Sandwiches would be cut up from the leg of mutton, all round the pickl
e
s would be handed out and everybody was enjoying themselves. But more or less we would be in bed. It would be just adults. To a certain part we would hear this and see it, and so heavy the dancing would go on, that the furniture, we had to hold the drawer
s
, for the vases dropping off. They would have dropped off 'cos of the creaky floor and so on. The floor was creaking and cracking. They'd say "Oh we'll send the floor if we do much dancing". But that was our happiness. There was no gramophones, there was 
no wireless sets and nothing at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was there anyone in the family who sang.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
My father sang. Took to the middle of the floor, front of the fireplace, his back to the fireplace and he'd sing the Old Swanny River, or something like that, all the d
itties. And my mother would sit in the corner and take her part singing and she had a good voice too. They both had good voices. And I was proud to hear them. My aunt would take her own song and she'd never seem to end there was so many verses to it. And 
we had to get her to stop. And then the party would break up somewhere about eleven o'clock, all very happy and good enjoyment. Yes we had happy days then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. But my father was always singing to us. The minstrel songs. Sometimes he'd black his face up as if he was a coon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What were the songs, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Swanny River, Oh Darkie does your heart grow weary. Oh I forget the others. And my mother would sing a few Irish songs - The Rose of 
Tralee, and another song but I forget the title.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your parents play any games with you, indoors?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes they used to play dominoes on the table on a Sunday evening. We'd play for halfpennys, our stakes would be halfpennys. And then after we'd g
ot tired of playing dominoes we used to build up the dominoes in kind of bricks. But I never seen any card games, or whist drive, it was mostly dominoes, or snap. Or we'd have something in your hand and we'd play tip it, which hand is the thing in. You pu
t your two hands out and you'd say "Now which is it?" And you'd just knock the other hand that wise, and you'd cross them over as to say no it's not that one, and then they had to find the hand and then it was their turn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about outdoor games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I was never keen on football or cricket myself. I mostly watched it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your mother and father didn't play outdoor games with you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes, we had books. Yes, we had plenty of books to read. But
 one paper came in on a Sunday but we never read the papers, only my mother and father. My father'd read the paper and hand it to my mother and he'd say "Now when you've read that paper tear it up so that the children wont read what's inside."
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What papers were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
It think it was what was called The Umpire, it later became The Empire. But we never read a newspaper and long after that we were nervous to read a paper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your father felt it fit literature for children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. He thought an
ything of divorce or anything wasn't for us, it had to go on the fire or destroyed completely. We never handled a bad paper or a bad book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now what about magazines, did you have magazines in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. No magazines came into the house, only it might be a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 atholic periodical, or a parochial magazine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did they ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No they probably read to themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Oh dear me, yes. Funerals were kind of elaborate affairs. I remember my Grandma's funeral, about 1908. I would be then six. It was a great funeral, my sister was there, all my sisters were there, but my youngest sister that was born in 1900 
and me, we'd seen all the bouquets of flowers going to the funeral and as I said it was an elaborate affair and we all had to go in strict rotation as the undertaker would line us up for the funeral. My mother went first because it was her mother, and my 
father followed next, and then the children in seniority.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 All the children attended, did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes all the children and all the family went. And the relations. Aunts and uncles. And then, we have four or five coaches. Horses, about four, must be 
black houses, and four to the corpse, the coffin. Four would pull the coach with the coffin in. Two for each of the other coaches. And the carriers would be sitting in the back. Probably if there wasn't enough coaches they'd sit up the front with the driv
e
r. The tall hats on the drivers. And you always brought in the drivers before the funeral started and they got something to drink. That was an undertaken thing, and it was always looked forward to. They would get a glass of whisky, or half a glass of whis
ky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Suppose it was a poor family, what happened then if they couldn't afford the whisky?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
I think it nearly always went, because whisky was cheap in those days. 10/- probably, may be less. Wine was about 2/6 a bottle. And then you'd go out, you'd 
have your large handkerchiefs - white bordered with black - it was a solemn affair. And you'd go out into the funeral and you'd watch the children cry, or watch the mother cry, or whoever it was. And the neighbours would watch whose wreath was kind of big
g
est, or where it came from. And then when you came back you got a lovely tea. Sometimes the best you'd ever had in a year. Boiled ham, pickles, it was elaborate. The old fashioned urn on the hearth and the woman who was cutting up the tea for us, nice whi
t
e apron and a black dress and she'd usher you into the dining room where we'd have our tea and she'd say "Now you must be cold coming from the cemetery" and we'd all be seated down and in no time we'd have the tea and a little drop of whisky put in your t
ea. Even the children. And then when you'd finished more tea was poured out and then we'd have a good time. Then we'd talk about all the old times, they were good people, good souls, and they must be at rest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about the clothes? What type of clothes did everyone wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 All black clothes. Costumes. Children, and I think I had a little black kind of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 Norfolk}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  suit - a belt round the side, in the middle, and a belt up each side. I think like what you'd call a plus four suit that came out, a kind of 
a golfing suit. We wore them and short trousers. The ladies probably wore a long dress, a very long dress touching nearly to their toes, always black. And a black coat if the weather was cold, black gloves and a handbag. The gentlemen wore black suits, co
llar and tie, black tie, and sometimes they'd be stiff collars then, the soft ones I don't think had hardly come out. Stiff turned butterfly collar - I sometimes think it might be a stiff collar attached to the false front - we used to call it the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 dickey}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  front. If your shirt wasn't too clean it'd cover it underneath.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me about the tipping that went on at the funerals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. When we got to the cemetery, the coffin is put down into the earth, a huge, deep, grave, The grave diggers, usual
ly two or three, would stand close by behind the mourners, and they'd look very mournful themselves. They'd have their cap in front of them, their hands in front, and their eyes cast down, and the head of the mourners used to say "Oh, the poor grave digge
r
s, they've dug this lovely grave." And they'd go over a shilling a two, and say "There you are, it's a nice grave you've dug, you've worked very hard." And he would say "Thank you Ma'am." Then another, they'd go round to them all, 'til about seven or eigh
t people probably gave 1/- or 6d each.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 It was a sort of collection for them all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Oh yes. And then when you were on your way back somebody would say "Oh I've forgot the grave diggers and they'd go into their purse and run back and the man would be
 half smiling because they thought they'd got away from the grave side but he was solemn again when he got the 6d. And then he'd start shoveling up nice and careful the earth on to the coffin. But that was quite a solemn affair for the grave diggers. It w
as a source of revenue for them, they got, well I think its even done now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 But they also tipped when they got back home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The coach drivers was brought into the house again and either had tea, or they said they was too busy to have tea, but they g
ot another drink again. Whatever it was. It was usually what we call 'short' stuff. Wine, or very often it was the whisky. They always made sure of that. If it was cold they'd be knocking their hands together and it was a sign before they went out to the 
funeral that the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 coachmen were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
 waiting for a drink before they started off. They could never start off 'til they got the drink and they could drive better. And when we went to the cemetery, it was up a very narrow lane - Moston lane, it was very narrow now 
it's wide - they could hardly get a coach up there and they thought at times it would rock over, nothing but bricks and slime and they got to the grave. But they were very solemn affairs them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you feel about it as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Not solem
n at all. We looked forward to it, and we was one day asking who was going to die next. So that we could get a big feast. And it was, oh, marvellous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember the custom of children going into houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes, we used to queue up at the door 
to see this lovely corpse. It was always a lovely corpse, and how beautiful she was, or he was, and very often we were too small to see into the coffin, we'd be lifted up by the person who let us in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother and father mind about this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
And we never cried. We said "Ah, what a pity, what a shame." And we'd run from school and knock at the door and be lifted up by the owner to peep into the coffin. But we never touched them. We'd just look and we never cried. It was something, not what we 
looked forward to, but we look forward to somebody else going that way so's that we could if it was belonging to us, we'd get this huge tea. My mother'd buy a large ham and cook it herself, probably the night before, and all have it ready.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How many funerals do you remember as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
There was my grandmother in 1908. Then there was my father in 1914, I was twelve then. Then there was an uncle somewhere around 1910. And that was all - the others came later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You've heard about an Irish wake - now were any of your parents of Irish descent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes, my father and mother were Irish descent. But we never kept the wake. They did stay up all the night in some cases. But they never waked in the place itself. They never smoked or drank.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What was a wake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Now a wake was where they'd all sit talking about the person who'd died, smoking, very often drinking, falling to sleep. But we never kept that ourselves. Me mother in the end, when others would die, she wouldn't stay up all night. She'd go 
to bed and put the coffin lid on to the coffin itself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The corpse would be in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The corpse would be in the front of the house - the parlour it were called. The coffin was on a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 trestle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  and laid out on white sheets. In the end I think we 
dispensed with those. Whereas if there was a wake they wouldn't put the lid on at all. They'd go in now and again after having a smoke and a drink to see if the corpse was alright. It hadn't walked out, because they always thought this would happen, and t
hey'd wake the corpse all the time. Walking - but that's mostly out in this country - it used to be kept on where Irish people went on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 It did happen when they came over to England too, didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. And then they'd have a trick, sometimes, if 
the corpse was likely to swell, they'd put a plate of salt on and all that kind of thing. They'd put a plate of salt on the body of the corpse, on the stomach in case it was swelling. 'Cos sometimes that did happen and they'd put salt in a saucer on the b
ody. The family would do that. And the candles would burn and very often you had to go in to see that the candles were burning, if they were careless the candles could burn down and a fire }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 
burn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  the corpse. This has happened in some cases, but never in ours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about the bouquets you carried?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well we had little posies of bouquets and we carried them out to the funeral and then when my grandmother was put into the earth we dropped them and then little bits of earth were thrown on the top. They were buried with my grandmother. I was then six.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember any of the women wearing veils?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
They used to wear long veils over their faces, yes. I think they called them, if it were the wife, widow's weeds. And the onlookers, people used to co
me and stare right into the funeral coach and say "Oh well, she's crying, she's really taken it to heart, she must have loved him, 'Cos she's crying so hard." 'Cos I suppose they thought if you didn't cry you didn't love him, you were glad to get rid of h
im.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And this was the idea to hide their faces?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. And of course "Oh she's taken it very hard, poor little children there, all them's left without a father and she'll have to work." Because there was no insurance, there was no welfare state or s
ocial security at all round about 1908, only pensions was just coming up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What happened when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 My father died in 1912. My sisters were working - three was in the mill. So my mother never, never worked. Her work was in the home.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What did your sisters do in the mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Two of my sisters were winders and one was a spinner. So hot was the mill that she was in her bare foot and I remember once she had to come off because she got a splinter in the sole of her foot. Very bad, be
cause they had to go into their bare feet because the heat was terrific in the cotton mill. Even the floor was hot, because you see it had to be kept at a certain temperature, the mill. But even if you was going on the stairs as I did one day go to the co
tton mill and take my sisters dinner, and I was nearly over - powered, fainting, with the heat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 She would take a packed lunch would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Sandwiches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. And sometimes if she wouldn't come home to dinner I'd take the dinner, her lunch for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And it was usually sandwiches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. Oh probably brawn sandwich, or a meat sandwich, boiled mutton which you can hardly get these days I'm told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your mother used to boil her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I'd take these because my sist
er wanted to keep on with her work. Sometimes they'd go on with their work in their dinner hour, which was forbidden, but they'd go on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Because of the wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. They'd get so much for a certain job. And I remember my sister that was a winder, 
they'd get somebody else's work would be spoilt and she said it usen't be fair getting somebody else's work when you'd done your own work. They had ruined it and you had to try to rewind it again for somebody else. And after that they started putting thei
r own names on the cops and the wheels so that we could get our own work back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 But did they get extra pay, of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. Because this bad work was thrown out and the overlooker used to find this bad work and used to share it out, and the good wi
nders used to suffer for the bad winders. No extra wages at all and that had to be done. And then there were the danger, my sister used to say, cleaning the machine while it was in operation, 'cos you could get caught and many times she's seen a girl what
 they called scalped, caught in the machine with long hair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They didn't make them wear caps or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
No. They didn't wear caps in those days. And they'd have to shout quickly to the overseer to turn off the power, and he'd switch off but some
times the damage was done. The hair was probably lifted with the scalp sometimes and carried to the hospital. It was very hard to get compensation, you had to fight because they'd say it was your own fault while the machine was in operation. Although rare
l
y the rules of the factory were pinned up at that time. I think it was later the factory rules came out. But they had to work because Friday was pay day and it was probably half a sovereign, and they run over the half sovereign and paper money came later 
a
nd they thought they'd have a good time. But rarely did they get a sovereign. And that was Friday and my mother would be waiting for the wages, very often her purse would be empty by the dinner time, she'd managed to get out the lunch and she was waiting 
f
or their wages and I used to see her and used to admire her, she'd get the wages, it was put on to the table and kind of pooled. Well the rent is on Monday, that's the rent. Then that's for the club money, there was always so much for insurance to bury yo
u
. She always saved up to bury you, you see, you must have a good funeral not a pauper's grave, you mustn't be buried by the parish. That was so much for the club money and so much for the rest of the week to keep us all in. And that's all the family plann
i
ng. My mother never went into debt. What she couldn't afford to buy she waited while she saved so much a week. Had probably a club card and so much in a little box but she never went what we call on 'tick', on the slate. They used to turn all their money 
u
p and it would just depend on whether they'd get a 1/- or 2/- because all their clothes were bought by my mother 'til they became probably twenty, up to twenty-one years. And I remember my mother used to follow the fashions of the day, and my sister said,
 "No, I'll just have a long coat instead of a dress."
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
And my mother used to be annoyed because she said "You're not fashionable like other girls." And they used to wear blouse and skirt at one time, with a tie attached, kind of a masculine thing, but
 they were very lovely, and what we call' leg of mutton' sleeves, full sleeves, and never very low cut, oh no, it was modest. And I used to see my mother always putting her hand to her neck, you see. Always modest. To her neck when she'd be talking to any
 
one. And they were very particular. And very particular talking in the house that the children would not hear anything that they should not hear. And I think we grew up like that into a good home and good example and fortunately we never went wrong. And I
 
look back now at my mother and think she was a saintly kind of a person, that she never envied anybody and very often people said "Oh, she's alright, her purse is full" but it wasn't. It was always empty towards the week. And she had to scratch and scratc
h and mend clothes and patch. Do her bedding, her patchwork bedding, and all her home was scrupulously clean. And we were never hungry and we was never in want.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Could you tell me if you had different food on Sunday for tea? Or any other special occasion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You mentioned high teas on Sunday. What did it consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Teas - well mostly we'd have ham, or home-made tea cakes, and celery in the old celery glasses, the tall glasses, and nothing elaborate.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 This was just mostly Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Just plain Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now did you have anything different for dinner on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes we had the roast leg of lamb, I've already said that, and plenty of potatoes and cabbage and rice pudding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were there any special occasions when you had anything different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No, only at Christmas time. Then we probably had pork. But no fowl. Rarely had fowl. Might be a chicken now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What order were you served in at meal? Was there any special order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 My father usually got served the first, he'd do the carving. I think I said that before. But there were no favourites.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who fed the younger children when they were unable to feed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well I was the youngest and I wouldn't remember much about the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you taken out visiting neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No not neighbours.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about friends and relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Very rarely. I used to go myself to visit my aunt. But I wasn't taken out by my father and mother. They were kind of house birds I think, they stayed at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 So you always went on your own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
No my mother used to do the shopping herself. And now and again I'd look out for her and if she was coming I'd go along and help to carry the groceries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I can't remember whether I did or not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember any other outings with your parents? Bank holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes. We'd go over to Belle Vue. We'd spend a day out probably at Walden, which was a long way from here in th
ose days, in the country. Or over to Delamere Forest and take sandwiches with us and that's all I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever go away for a holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We used to always go to Southport for a week. My father worked on the railway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you go every year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. And he got the passes for himself and my mother and the children and we'd spend a week. And we used to play about in the sand with a bucket and spade, making mud pies and so on. We thoroughly enjoyed ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The whole family went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes. And we used to come back looking quite well and brown.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your activities were mostly on the sands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Could you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes, well Saturday wasn't much different from the rest. There we
re still people worked on a Saturday, the half day holiday hadn't come in. And my sisters worked 'til twelve o'clock or one o'clock cleaning down frames. But there was nothing particular. People used to come up cleaning - buckets all along the street and 
doing the kerbs and flagstones, all the steps nicely creamed and joining with one another. And making it so picturesque. The fronts was immaculately clean and the windows and everything. And Saturdays was done like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 That was how your mother spent Saturdays, but how did you spend your Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well we'd go to the pictures. There was silent films. I think it was 2d. We went to one, it had only just been opened. I think 1912. I was ten. It was the King's Picture House in Regent Road, now burn
t down a few weeks ago. And we thought we were very wealthy with 2d. We got in the best seats. Oh, I think 3d the best seats, we went in the 2d. We tried hard to get 3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 rd}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  to get in the best seats. They was plush seats. We wasn't snobbish but we thought we w
ere it, and we were laughing at the people down in the 2ds. Of course that was a lot of money because we got our Saturday 1/2d or Saturday 1d usually on a Friday night, but that's when we went to the pictures, silent. And when the cowboys was on, the pian
o would roar and there'd be banging on to make it so, coming down the mountains as if hell, and we used to bang on the piano to make it elaborate, because there were no talkies. And that's how I spent my Saturday afternoons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How about Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Su
nday was an important day. We were Catholics, we went to Mass on a Sunday. We were all, what they'd call the Children's Mass, we went at nine o'clock. We all was there, packed out, up middle aisle. And we had our tickets to show our teacher on a Monday th
a
t we'd been. We'd get little tickets on a Sunday to show that we'd been and on a Monday morning they used to ask who'd been to Church, who'd been to Mass, and there was no getting out of it because we turned our tickets up at Church. The teachers were alw
ays present, everyone of the teachers, from the Headmistress down. And those tickets who was missing, they knew who was missing, because they hadn't got their tickets. And they had the role call. And it wasn't kind of forced, we went freely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 But were they cross if you didn't go and you hadn't got your ticket?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. In some cases they'd have the cane if they didn't have a proper answer. If somebody wasn't ill at home or they was sick. But usually they was sick or something like that and there was a 
note sent by the mother that they was sick. Sometimes they wasn't sick at all they just didn't go, or they overslept. That was Sunday morning. We went to Church in the evening. I always went and my mother and father went. My father, as I have said before,
 was prominent, he was in one of the poor societies at Church, and he was very keen on looking after the poor. And always at Church, and my mother came, quite stately and sedately.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me something about your festivals at Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 Well we had our May Crownings, May Day. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
The crowning of the statue. This is general all through the Catholic churches throughout the country. Yes, throughout England and over to Ireland and Scotland. And May Day is the crowning of the Queen and we crown a statue 
of Our Lady, a kind of memorial thing. The statue means nothing to us because it is chalk and plaster and all that kind of thing, but we crown it, we honour it as a queen. You have a child about seven or eight - they usually put their names in a hat and t
h
e children themselves pick out the name, and the one who is picked out is the May Queen. Even then that causes jealousy, when it's picked out quite harmlessly. People say, "oh yes, they've been favoured, that's been specially put in, "when it hasn't. That
'
s one of the festivities. And, of course, we have our processions round the church. We'd have our men's processions on special occasions when the men used to meet. Because there was a Men's Society and a Men's Confraternity and we'd have the processions l
i
ke what we call the children of Mary, used to wear a kind of blue cloak, and they'd have their festivities, unfortunately though these have nearly all gone out. I don't say the Church is losing it's way but they've gone out. People have less interest now 
than they had then. Then the usual Whit week came. The Whit week processions. The Whit Friday procession.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The men wore a cloak and you walked on a certain day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. We were a kind of bodyguard. What we call in our Church the Breast of Sacrament.
 Guild. And we walked behind that. We carried a canopy. We wore red sashes. Our badges that we belonged to that. We were members of a Confraternity. And the women had their own Catholic Women's League.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And they also walked, did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. But no
t as much as the men. But they had their own meetings, and discussions, not really gossip, some were gossips but they went on to see what they could do to aid the parish in extra funds what it needed. And if they run a concert in them days and got }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11090850 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 10 or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11090850 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
15 they thought they were very rich, because there was no such thing as Bingo or Pools or Football Clubs that the Church tries to aid on now to get things to repair the church. It's a costly job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now could you tell me about Whit week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well Whit 
week, is Whit Friday to us Catholics and we have our gigantic procession through Manchester when 20,000 people take part. And we take part in that leaving, oh we were up, as children we probably never slept all night, we was very excited, up at six o'cloc
k in the morning, ready and crying if it rained. A nice day. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 The knocker-up would even come and say: "Well it's a nice morning this morning, a little bit of wind but it won't do any harm." }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And then we'd get ready for our procession. My younger sister was only eighteen months older than me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid786894\charrsid9511872 
She'd have a bouquet or a basket of flowers or at one time they used to have crooks with dummy flowers (small copy of shepherd's staff with imitation flowers) and they'd take part and move off from the church at eight o'cl
ock in the morning arriving in Albert Square scheduled time.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did they walk all the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about the little ones?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Nobody under seven had to walk. Though they did push them in, and that was forbidden. They May Queen walked but 
she hadn't to have a train. She could walk but nobody was allowed to wear the train and nobody carried it. And they walked back very tired and then when we got back there was always buns and milk waiting for us, the cakes and the milk, big cans of milk, b
eing ladled out by the men and the women and handing it to the children. Oh it was a happy day. A tiring day because we used to go to bed almost immediately we were tired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me about the prejudice against the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes there was a gr
eat prejudice in them days, happily it's going away now, as it should be. The Church of England procession walked first on the Monday which was the Protestant Church. And they said "Well it's our day now, we've had our day, we don't care what happens it c
a
n rain as much as it likes and it'll help to pour on the Catholics." Of course Friday came, we were looking forward to it and we was hoping it didn't pour, many prayers were said it didn't pour and it didn't pour, but very often we got our share of this r
a
iny weather. Oh we did get it tremendously wet. And we used to go out defying the weather, but if it rained before we started the wise priest would never let us go, although we children wanted to go and we were upset. And we used to be the same, there was
 faults on both sides. We said "We've had our day now and it was very fine" and they'd be singing in the pubs on the Monday the old British songs, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 ongs of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 the Bull Do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
g breed, and all this and on the Friday they'd be going back to Ireland and singing their 
Irish songs. It was remarkable, we've had our day and not say anything about the Catholics on that day nor the Church of England on Monday one avoided it, though we did go to see one another's processions, hoping ours was the best. And very often we becam
e the highlights. There was a lot of prejudice because even the schools were prejudice. We had to fight for our schools, the Catholic teachers for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 atholic children, and I remember quite well, I was still seven, but I don't remember what was on the banners 
because I didn't take any notice. I wouldn't take any notice of the banners, we walked, we learnt how to walk first from school. We used to have a practice two days before Whit Friday and the pitch would be bubbling up amongst the sets in the road and you
'd get your feet all covered in pitch when you tried to walk on the tram lines four abreast, and there was four lines, and we was always trying to walk on the lines and it was a terrific heat. And then that went on and we were quite happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 But was there any prejudice apart from trying for the best procession?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. My father used to say when he tried to, when there was jobs advertised, no Irish need apply outside the works, no Catholics need apply outside the works. And if it was known you were Iri
sh descent, we were only Irish descent, third generation, My mother was born in Manchester as I've said before, but her mother, my grandmother, were Irish. But there were the prejudice. And I've heard my father saying you had to change your name if it was
 anything like an Irish name. You would not be employed. And it was going to be very hard. Same if girls went into service it was very hard. I remember 30 or 40 years ago where it was in the paper no R.C. need apply. But that happened in my father's day.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you find prejudice among the common people though, apart from employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh the common people, yes. They were the worst. You found it, yes, very much indeed. You found it during the elections.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What form did it take?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well they'd say
: "Oh you're a Roman; you're a Roman Catholic; we'll have nothing to do with him; they're always at Church; they're a lot of hypocrites." Which wasn't true, people hadn't analysed what we went to church for. But we found it going to school. We used to say
 
the same 'proddy-dogs'. We erred on both sides. We had both our faults. And the others used to say 'cat-licks'. And we used to fight sometimes coming home. We didn't have our gangs exactly, but we used to team up and say "Watch that now, somebody's going 
to call us." But we was on our metal. We'd prepare for it like the Boy Scouts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You never saw arguments between neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. It would come out. The arguments would come out in the end. It had to come out. Fights were frequent happening in stre
ets. People in the ordinary working class, which I belonged to, the working class. It came out frequent and it was terrible to see two women fighting, especially when they'd pull each other's hair. It could be painful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You've seen this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes, it could happen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 That would be between Protestants and Roman Catholics would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Not necessarily. It could happen and there's a remarkable thing, a laughable one. You'd get a Cathy, wearing probably a shawl on the shoulders and said "Well we've 
had our day" and come laughing. And one woman I remember threw her shawl quite off the floor and tread on the tail of me coat. It was remarkable. "How dare you, and I come from Liverpool where the Irish fought and we've had our day and it's been beautiful
"
 and they're disappointed the other side, they was wishing it would rain but they haven't had it. Oh they were disappointed. But they all celebrated now in the pub and were none the better for it. All quite happy. And as I say, all those things are happil
y, happily, going away. We are all mixing with one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you have different clothes on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Oh yes. We had what we called our Sunday best. It was put away for Sunday in the drawer. I don't think we had a wardrobe then. It was nicely f
olded in the drawer. I remember I had a kind of sailor suit, it was velvet and a wide collar collar full size like a sailor, and short velvet trousers, and I think there were brass buttons down and buttons up the side of the trousers and a little tie. I t
h
ink I was fair with a bit curly hair in those days. Nice black shoes and white socks. And we dare not dirty them. But we did dirty them but we got a telling off. But it was kept on for the full day. It was never taken off, after an hour, it was kept on. A
nd then carefully put away and the collar was nicely washed and starched and ironed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about your mother and father and sisters, they all had special Sunday clothes did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. My mother she used to very often go in black and sometimes a f
eather. A long feather of plumes, a boa, or whatever they called them, a long feather, and that pins sometimes to fit them on. Long hat pins to stick it to the other side. No safeguard on the other side though, stick it right through. Very often they stuc
k it through the top of their head and scalp. And nice black costumes my sisters had. But one sister would never wear a black costume or coloured costume at all, she'd wear a dress and a coat to cover it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 She wasn't particular, but the other ones always wore a costume and was very, very proud of herself.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you play games on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. As I think I've repeated before after our Sunday's tea my father would play dominoes. We'd play for half }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 pennies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 . My mother'd join in. And never cards. And tip it. And that's all we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your parents think it wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes, in a sense we did. There was no Sunday work exactly on a Sunday in them days. Very remote. I don't remember any works factory working on a Sunday it was probably alarmed and viewed with...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How about working in the house though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Oh yes, do the necessary work. Not really cleaning up. We had our meals. And what was necessary, clean round the hearth. But we never cleaned outside that was already done
 on Saturday. But we'd what we called take the ashes out from the grate and throw them into the tip or the dustbin at the back, and all was prepared before dinner, then we'd have our dinner. But we never did any work on a Sunday. In the afternoon we'd go 
t
o the Sunday School which I belonged to and the older men and women of the parish occasionally then used to meet together and we'd get prizes for the best attendance. It was a great day that. Yes great days. The men would give the prizes for the boys and 
the girls would take the girls, you see, and their prize, and they'd go out quite sheepishly and receive our prize.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Why sheepishly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well we were shy, we were young and we were going among big people and they seemed giants to us, these young men a
nd women, probably only about seventeen or eighteen. And we was led by the hand usually and we went up to our prize, probably a medal or a nice framed picture of an angel, a guardian angel, as they painted in those times, almost on the verge of falling ov
er the rocks, which wasn't true. Angels never did those things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever have Mothering Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
No I don't remember Mothering Sunday then, not in those years. I think it's quite a new idea. The women had in my day what they called Confratern
ity. The married women went to theirs and the young single women had their own confraternity and they all went out to help the church in this way in their own different organisations which it went into the one pool, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your parents both attended a place of worship did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They were Roman Catholics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How often did your mother and father go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We went Sunday morning and we went Sunday evening. They both did. And I went Sunday afternoon from 2 'til about 3 for the Sunday school.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were there any Sunday School outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
We might have a run out, a day out, a few hours somewhere quite close too, but they always seemed to be a long way away. Peel Green even which was only a few miles from here, about 4 miles, was a long way in those days because ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The old tram cars.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Horse trams?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No I was just too late for the horse trams. They'd be about 1902 or 1903. The electric came up later. But it was the old open car an
d if it was raining woe betide you, if you got on the top, you was drenched through. And the old trolley, it used to often come off the wires, and the trolly boy'd be at the front trying to put it down and it would stop if it came off the trolley lines at
 
the electric wire and we'd get all wet through. And the man driving at the front used to bang it down with a clang. And we'd go out to Peel Green or Worsley and we'd thought we were absolutely in the country. We went mad running about the grass, playing a
b
out, tiring ourselves out, playing all kinds of games, going over stiles and going near the pond, and teachers after us saying "don't go too far, don't get lost", and we had a roll call periodically. Sunday School was a happy time it kept us together and 
w
e always came home hungry and tea was about six o'clock, but we always had something waiting for us even when we came home at half past three, you see. We had some cakes and some milk waiting for us. In those days we used to get a lot of buttermilk. It wa
s very cheap and good and we liked it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were there any social activities organised by the church? And did you take part in any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well there was concerts at school. We went on concerts. The boys and girls they'd go on concerts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You acted in them did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. We'd sing. Organised by the school teachers. And we'd probably sing altogether. They'd find a good voice and one voice would sing individually. And the room would be packed out. They'd come to hear us for 6d and 1/- a time. Very crow
ded rooms and there'd be 40 or 50 boys singing, because you know they had 50 boys in a class in them days, and they could manage them quite well because we was under strict discipline. And we had our concerts. And my sister was in a concert, and I think t
hey was shepherds or something, and some song they was singing, I forget the song now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your church run a temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Not in my time. I think I've heard my mother saying the blue }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 ribbon}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  army or 
something like that. Or she belonged to it once. Something about blue ribbons, it was a kind of temperance, not a band of hope. But my father was teetotal although he didn't belong to a temperance for 20 years then he broke it I'm told on Mafeking night, 
that would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  1900, Boer war, and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 bonfire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
 was made and my mother said "oh the bonfires was great. I wasn't born then. But I wasn't in a temperance club or a society, but some did. They were very active the temperance society at that time, but I didn't belong to one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you belong to any other club organised by the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We said it individually. My mother used to say "Now before you start your meal say your grace." We said grace at schoo
l then, to make sure we had said grace we said it as a body, but when we got home it was always grace was said and we said it ourselves to ourselves. And as the meal was put out we were never allowed, we wasn't jumped upon if we didn't but we was always t
old to say grace before meals and after meals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes we had family prayers when the family gathered together. Yes we had our own prayers. If my father wasn't in, or were working late, my mother would start o
ff. Oh yes. And when we were young and going to bed at night my mother would put us to bed quite young and as I've said before, the old lamp would go down and we'd have the last prayers of my mother repeating and we'd repeat it afterwards. And then she sa
id the light would go down. Gradually she'd turn the wick down in the oil lamp and it was peace and she'd go down quietly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he talk about it a great deal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well we were Liberal. And
 the election at that time 1910, I think there was two elections the same year - January, and there was a snap election at the end. And in 1906 Mr. Belloc had come to Salford, a complete stranger, to defend the seat in the interest of the Liberals. He was
 
going to beat, as he said, one of the giants of the Conservative Party in this area, Mr. James Grimble Groves, who was a local brewer and was well known. He was a director of Groves and Wittnals and he was certain, in his own words, to get in. He'd alread
y represented Salford South, which is now East Salford, since 1900-1906. When Mr. Belloc came he said "I come as a stranger. I'm a Catholic (because prejudice was on). You can vote for me if you like, or you can send me back to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Arundel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 , Sussex." But he was a speaker. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 
Mr. Belloc got many Conservative voters into his own party. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
When they heard Belloc they said "This is the man." At the count (which I was not there because I was only four, but my father tells me all this) they went and it was almost fever heat.
 And my sister, the one born in 1888 said "We went along to Leicester Square with our red rosettes and before we arrived there they were taken out. There were frequent battles with the Conservatives and we fought back. We had a fight before we got to Leic
e
ster Squire but we managed to got to Leicester Square and we got our red rosettes back again." When they came to the town hall and Mr. Belloc was the first, his voice completely gone hoarse, passed the vote of thanks, he said "I came, I saw, I conquered."
 
I think he won by 432 votes. Men's votes only because the franchise for women wasn't until 1918. Mr. Groves of course had said he would win the election but he didn't. He was downhearted, he was upset, and the taunts of his supporters was "Are we downhear
t
ed - no." But they actually were. Mr. Belloc I'm told, was carried shoulder high to the Liberal Club in Trafford Road and Mr. Groves, too, received as much congratulation outside his own Conservative Party as the victor, but he retired from the fray. Now 
1910, which I do remember, but didn't take any part in the election, with the exception of going for photographs of Mr. Belloc, and they were huge photographs. And my mother plastered the window with the photographs of Mr. Belloc.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your mother was Liberal too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Oh yes. In red and green, because green was home rule for Ireland and they'd nearly got it through. And this time when Mr. Belloc came along in the carriage with his wife the cheering was frantic and the next door neighbour couldn't find a re
d handkerchief but she actually took her red and waved it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 And Mr. Belloc's smiles went. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Others, the Conservatives waiting for a bucket of water to throw on him. But the bucket of water was actually taken off the woman and thrown over herself, by one of Mr. Belloc's supporters. That was while they were actually waiting. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Mr. Belloc's supporter took off this woman, very antagonistic, bitter, she wanted to drown Mr. Belloc either with water or sludge. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Absolutely bad feeling.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you think religion had anything to do with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. Yes, I think so. And South Salford knew that religion could conquer it. They knew that Catholics could win the seat. And they knew the Catholics had the sway because if they pressed the button the Catholics could change the 
election. Win it or lose it. Because in the area there was four churches and the electorate must have been written in only a thousand in each church and they was voters, that would be 4000 and when you think there was 7000 in the cathedral parish, 3000 in
 the parish not very far away - St. Peter's, 3000 in my own parish, and 3000 in another parish, we could have carried the election.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you told who to vote for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We were never told who to vote for only when it was a case of the school quest
ion. When our schools were in jeopardy and the candidate never gave any yes or no, proper answer to the question "Would you, if elected into parliament vote for the interest of the Catholic schools?" If he said "No.", or "No question," we would not vote. 
A
nd if Mr. Belloc said "Yes, to the best of my ability. Yes." Many Catholics of course voted for Mr. Groves and others for Mr. Belloc. And many Conservatives voted for Mr. Belloc when they heard his speech. Because he was an orator, a debater, at Oxford Un
iversity, and had been for many years, and he captured them. And then Mr. Belloc came out. He decided that Parliament was trickery. Politics was humbug. And he took to writing. His first book I think was "Change in the Cabinet".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Why do you think your father held the Liberal view?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't really know myself why he held liberal. May be because it was the home rule for Ireland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Liberals felt that Ireland should have home rule?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes, the Liberal party did at that time. Gladstone, you see,
 was pushing the bill through. It wasn't Gladstone's parliament, I don't think in 1910, but I think that was mostly it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 The home rule was swerving to the Liberal party.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 This was why your mother held the Liberal view too, was it?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How would it affect them - home rule for Ireland?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
The Irish voters came from Belfast. There was also at Westminster such as Redmond. John Redmond was the representative for Ireland in Westminster Parliament and he was a great man, a great orator, and did 
much work. It was also solving the poor question and whether the Conservatives was really antagonistic. The upper ten, kind of people, aristocrats, landed gentry, plenty of money. But there was no special reason, I don't think, why he voted Liberal.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did they think the working man had a square deal in those days or did they think one particular party gave it to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't think they thought the working man had a square deal because they didn't. We had to work very, very hard indeed for 50 or 60
 hours a week, and very little pay. And almost sweated labour, one or two worked very hard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you hear your parents talk about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes I did. The many hard times when you think children were running bare footed, no shoes. I've seen that myse
lf. Boys have been selling papers in their bare feet. It was a common thing. And my father, who was the head of his own society at church organisation used to be stopped very often coming home from work from the railway. If he had any spare tickets in his
 pockets He'd given them to go to certain shops to get clogs, it was mostly clogs in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever wear clogs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. We wore clogs and brass round the edges and very well polished. They had to be well polished and nice because we had a 
school master who would look and he'd go right to back to see if the backs were polished as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The tickets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes. He'd get the clogs, there was a certain cloggers there, not far from here, Hudson Lane. And next time he'd meet the children t
he clogs had gone in the pawn shop for a few coppers, and sometimes may be for drink, I don't know, it might not be true. Or still further in debt. But he was easy and he loved the poor and he was very often imposed upon with his own money, and I found la
ter that my mother had to meet him coming home on a Friday for his wages, otherwise somebody else would meet him and his wages would be gone, before he'd arrived home. He couldn't see poverty by adults or children, and he was very often imposed upon.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your father felt that the working man had a really rough deal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh a really rough time at that time. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember his views in any detail about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. We had a hard life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did he chat about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 To my mother. Yes. You se
e I was only 12. But he said you had to get on with your work and you'd to keep up to your time, otherwise you'd lose your job. There was always somebody waiting at the door for it. You had to do a certain amount and the foreman had his favourites. And if
 you wasn't in with the foreman or didn't bribe him (take him to the local pub frequently, probably every night) you'd had it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 But how could the working man afford it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 In them days they used to say they'd draw it on the slate. Kind of credit 'til
 the weekend. At great risk I'm told, because the brewer couldn't get the money. That really did happen. They'd order it and pay at the weekend. There was a lot going on like that. Of course the pubs in those days was open at 6 o'clock in the morning, and
 children were taken in as well. From 6 in the morning 'til 11.00 at night. All day long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember your father voting in a General Election then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes I do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How about your mother, did she vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well she didn't vote then because it was only the men. It was a franchise for men only.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did your mother feel about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
She was part of the election dressing up the window. And going to the meetings. But in the main it was usually the men who went there. And the men carried the victory. Oh, she was interested very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 After 1918 who did she vote for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The votes really changed then. Liberal had died the death and the Labour Party was coming up and we went }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Labour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  because we thought they was the next best thing to th
e working class. We had a kind of horror of voting for the Conservatives. It was probably what had been brought up with you. They wasn't out for us. We wouldn't get a square deal. They were looked upon as not the type for the working class. And I've seen 
t
hem run up the street, say after 1918, say 1924, and take the whole thing and one would be feared (frightened) of the mob running up the streets, of Conservatives from one end of the street to the other. Because only down the road here was the Conservativ
e Club and before the election they'd be frantic if they thought they was going to lose the election and they'd run up with handbills and bells and your windows, if you had a Labour bill in the window, was in danger of being smashed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever have yours smashed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We had Liberal in. The windows weren't smashed but covered with dirt and sludge that children threw coming home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The children were taught to throw?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes. "Take him out, take him out," the children would say an
d me mother would come quickly to the step and tell them to get away and they'd stay there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember telling me about a fight and your mother bringing people into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 That was during the seamen's strike of 1911. The cotton mills, t
hat was where my sisters worked, had to come out because there was no coal to supply the mills and at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Howarth's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
 Mill my sister tells me, young Howarth led the horses by the reins up with the coal cart to the mill. But they was huge heavy deep coal carts an
d the men strikers tipped them up. They were chased by the police up the streets, the strikers, big burly policemen, and battoned down. In this very house my mother opened the door and they rushed down the lobby, now what we call the hall, and we looked t
h
rough the window and we actually seen, I did myself, I was nine, seen them being battoned down outside while they were on the floor. A cluster of men, three or four together and the police were livid, absolutely livid. Because others was throwing at them 
s
tones, and as the stones was being thrown the battons were being used more ferociously. At that time they were outnumbered, the police. And then there was an outcry and the mayor had ruled that the Riot Act was read and the military was brought in, the Sc
o
ts Greys at that time, and was mentioned later by the member for South Salford when he was putting up, Mr. Joe Tool. He said "Yes, I remember too the Scots Greys being brought in and within a few days of them coming there was peace." And then the women ha
d
 a march, I'm told. This was pitiful. I never seen it because I kept to my home because I was still at school, being nine years of age. A thousand women marched and it was agonising I believe, most of them hungry, down Trafford Road to town. Trafford Road
,
 Chapel Street on to Piccadilly and bystanders gave into their collecting boxes as collection and at one stand they gave milk for the children. They carried their own babies with them, younger children. And this was the highlight of the strike. It brought
 things to a head. It kind of softened the masters and the directors who were very hard hearted, who wouldn't give in to any increase in wages, and they got what they wanted. The dockers were victorious. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 And then there seemed to be ever anxious strikes after that, because everybody was coming out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
But my oldest sister went to one of the relief centers, unknowns to my mother, and brought about two or three leaves, and margarine and my mother said "Where have you brought that from?" "Oh, I went round to one of
 the relief centres and got it. I said I had five children." And mother said "You haven't got five children, you're not even married." And she said "Oh well we can't go hungry." And so we was all right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your father was affected by it, was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember your father saying that he risked losing his job or his house if he voted differently from his employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I never heard him say that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you know of anyone else this happed to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. But the fear was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 He felt he was under pressure?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The fear was there, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 From whom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
From employers. The fear was there. If it was known that he was Liberal. It was a common thing, I think, that in Groves Brewery that most of the employees voted for Groves, and 
worked for him. In honour to save their own jobs. It didn't apply to the railway I don't think. No. Because more or less they were all together. But in the other case it was different. Their employer was a candidate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 So your father didn't feel under any pressure to vote for a particular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. But the danger was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You mean if he changed his job it was always there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. I remember in those days he was slightly going grey, he went grey very quickly. And he used to try and chang
e his hair, dyes wasn't out in those days, and the soot from the chimney he used to get that mix it with butter and put it on, and of a weekend his hair was snow white when he'd washed it. He did that to appear younger because if you looked older your job
 was finished. It seemed you were getting old you couldn't get on. He was always afraid it would put him out. I don't know whether it was official or not, or just his own whim.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was your father a member of a political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't think he was ever a member. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did either of them work for any of the parties at an election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When your parents were not doing their work, how did they spend their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well I couldn't say exactly. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
No she didn't. Her home came first. And she wasn't neighbourly. We didn't invite neighbours into the home very much. We had one woman in now and again and my mother would give her some clothes to wash re
ally to help herself. She was a very poor woman and my mother used to give her something, scrubbing the clothes or something in order to help her. But we wasn't on par with neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 She didn't have any interests outside the home really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I can't remember, unless she went over to see my aunt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who did she go with then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When your father got home from work in the evenings how many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well I think he spent them all. Saturday evening he might go out to the local pub. But I remember going to the Regent Theatre - it was the Opera House, not the theatre next door - and the silent pictures. And we used to go there. My mother used to go 
there and I remember going there with him. I was only small. He had to take me because I was the youngest. And in between the pictures there was a singer came on, Tom Sherlock, who used to sing very sentimental songs to do with the picture. They put a pic
t
ure on and sing. "The Ship That Would Never Return" and a ship and a sailor there and the ship not returning home. And I was carried on his back, I was probably six years of age and I was tired. And they'd enjoy themselves that Saturday evening. But more 
o
r less he'd have his own favourite pub, never a boozer, never a drinker, he was teetotal for twenty years, 'til he broke and then he had his favourite place. But my mother never went into a public house, but she would have a drink at home. If my aunt came
 down to see her my aunt would run out with a jug and bring it in. And then they'd talk, and we had no wirelesses, we didn't even have a gramophone then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When did your father get home from work in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 About six o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How many evenings a week would you say he would spend in the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Every evening nearly. He was busy with his correspondence. Sunday evening he would stay in and people came to him for his help. In fact people came in and he taught them how to write, how to compose a letter, how to read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you know many people who couldn't read and write in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. My mother taught somebody how to read. Very patiently. My mother was a good scholar. Both of them. And yet in their day she tells me we could 
have pleased ourselves whether we went to school or not because there was no Education Act. But she said my grandmother brought in a private tutor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your father attend any clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't think he was a member of any club. Clubs didn't spring 
up very quickly, in those days. Mostly it was in the local that they talked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How often did he go to the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well I think only on a Sunday. Now and again he'd call on his way home but never to stay all the night. Wages was always safe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now your mother didn't go to pubs but she went on picnics did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
May be with a church picnic. If they was running a picnic the women, she'd go on, down to Wales or Holywell, or something like that. But she'd have to be saving so much a week on a card. 6d a week and sometimes she'd have to miss if she hadn't got it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your father take part in any sport? Did he attend the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. But he liked a bet, and my mother would, now and again. But they never went out to it. And it never interfered 
with the housekeeping money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you father or mother belong to any savings clubs, like a boot club, or a sick club, or a funeral club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. We used to save for clothes, probably at school banks or she'd save in a grocery club for special occasio
ns like Christmas - so much a week on a card. People had what they called the diddlum clubs and the knick knack clubs. A diddlum club was you paid so much money each week and one got it one week and one the next and so on. Some would say "Oh, I'm not payi
n
g it all to get the last chance. She's got the first and she's only paid the first installment and I've paid for mine by the last." Which was quite true. And with the knick knack club they'd draw up the numbers on paper and put in a begin and you'd take y
o
ur pick. And if you got no. 4 you'd have it the fourth week. And you'd get a card to go to this shop and buy clothes on the fourth week. It was the only way of saving as much as 4d or 6d. Everyone paid the same stake. A form of saving to get something for
 the house or clothes or shoes, anything like that. And the funerals, well towards that they saved in the club books. The men came and it was always said "We must make sure of a decent burial."
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you get on with your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They liked me
. I wasn't spoilt, but they went out to help me a great deal and I was the favourite. And I got on very well with my sisters. The one who was on par with me - eighteen months difference - and the one much older, who was working long before I was ever work
ing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was there one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes my first sister. The sister born in 1888. I was very close to her, she died only twelve months age, aged 80. We were very clannish and I miss her very much without brooding. We liked one another immensely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 As a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
We played with neighbour's children. We played outside. My sister used to play shuttle cock. We'd play top and whip, and what we'd call 'Piggy in the stick', knocking a piece of wood off, and roun
ders, and rally o, going down different streets and making hares and hounds on the kerbs. Hares and hounds we used to call it, you'd make an arrow on the street flags and you had to follow the arrow and chase them, and they'd go quickly round making arrow
s
 in the direction they'd gone, and we had to chase them and find them. That's all nice enjoyment 'till it was getting dusk, or in the summer time seven or eight, and even if it was light we were called in. And we'd probably have some milk when we got into
 the house and read our own little prayer books, our favourite books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes we were allowed to get dirty and wash ourselves. The water was waiting, a big yellow bowl of water, plenty of the old carboli
c soap. I remember sometimes instead of the towel we'd use an old }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Hessian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
 apron and dry ourselves quickly, because we'd be very dirty and rather than dirty the towel we'd use this for the first wash, and then we'd go on to the proper towel which was a nice
 hand towel. Mother would say, "Oh, you've got very dirty, where the devil have you been to, dirtying like this. Now polish your clogs for morning and put your clothes away tidy for the morning and you'll not be running around looking for your things." Ye
s, we were allowed to get dirty, and we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes, we had no discrimination. We played with anybody. Sometimes children was naughty and was hard to get on with. I think I had a small fight with one an
d was one woman came running and saying I'd nearly murdered her boy, and my mother saying "Well if he's nearly murdered him, your boy must have nearly murdered him."
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you belong to any youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I should now like to ask y
ou about how you spent your free time when you were at school. Did you have any hobbies then? Did you keep any pets, collect anything or do gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No pets. No hobbies, no gardening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well how did you spend your spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I liked readi
ng and writing. I used to practice writing at home and imitated my father how he wrote because I admired his writing. And I used to love reading and picking out stories and thinking I was the hero of the story. But no football, it didn't appeal to me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No fishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Walking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Walking, yes. I was a good walker. I used to walk to the parks and back home again tired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. I think I was turned against that, because I went with a friend who tr
ied to teach me to ride a bicycle and I was doing very well and then he suddenly lot go at the back and down I went and I got a nice bump on my forehead and I thought that's the end of that. It did unnerve me and I didn't take to riding a bike at all, tho
ugh I would have liked to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When you went for walks who did you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Always on my own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 School sports, yes. We used to go to Belle Vue and take part in the running. I never won. I'd practice gettin
g to the tape but I was always second or third to get to the tape.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you go to theatres? Now you told me you did go to some theatres?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes we went to the Regent Theatre, which later became the Palace Theatre, I went there when I'd be about four
teen or fifteen, that'd be 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Would this be while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh no, no theatres during school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about concerts then, or music halls, cinemas, did you go to those while you were still at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes we went to th
e cinema Saturday afternoons. Just the still pictures, and I've repeated that before. We went about two o'clock and came out about half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Probably. Did we get 6d. I don't know. We might have d
one. I think I only got 6d or 1/- when I first started work. We got about 3d every week, I think it went to the school bank on a Monday morning. I think me mother gave me that 3d out of her own pocket to save towards Whit week clothes and then 3d for pock
et money and that would have to go 2d for the picture house and 1d for sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother have anyone outside the home help her look after her house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. We had occasionally a woman come in but not often, to run errands, or if we t
ook ill take us over to Salford Royal Hospital if anything did happen. Something did happen to me when I was about six. I remember the old fashioned sinks, slop stones as we called them, and one of these must have been placed into the yard we must have be
e
n getting a new one, and I toddled out and down it came on my toe. My cries and yelps must have brought my mother and I was put into an old fashioned pram and rushed off by this good woman to Salford Royal Hospital. My toes today is just squeezed up. This
 woman used to come in and do a bit of washing because she was a poor woman, poorer than us, she'd a kind of husband who'd work when he liked and bad, and she was waiting for the next meal. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 
And if we had a huge hot pot or potato pie the leftovers was given to her and carried to her because she lived close by. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And any bread or old clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage? Who looked after you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well my father part of the time. When my mother went into hospital, whic
h I don't remember, probably I'd be about two, she went into hospital into Salford Royal for an operation on her leg. And my mother used to say "Oh father run the home very well with Mrs. So and So." I said "Did my father manage?" "Oh yes, he looked after
 us all."
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who looked after your mother when your sisters were born then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't know, because even the next to me, there was eighteen months. I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 An aunt lived close, my mother's sister. She lived in the next street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How much did you see of her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Two or three times a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did they share the same friends, your parents and your auntie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. My aunt had her own friends, and my mother didn't bother too m
uch. My mother hadn't too many friends herself. Acquaintances, but she never took anybody to go out with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your father have any friends of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. He met them when he went to the pub and talked, but never brought them along, with the exception of men in his own church affairs.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. But our relatives came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 So friends didn't call in casually then if you didn't have a lot of friends come to the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And I remember you telling me neighbours didn't. Now did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
My mother if she thought anybody was sick or lonely, she'd go and visit them, read to them and very often take them something to eat and have a chat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Pe
ople often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements. Now you told me about your parents having their Sunday night shindigs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh our amusement was really hectic. Because now and again a man would come, an old friend of the family, from
 Ireland and stay with my aunt. The fiddle was always brought from Ireland and hung up in the corner of the house ready to play. Well our house was the famous rendezvous for them coming down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Many people divide society into different social classes or
 groups. In that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well I think shopkeepers might have kept to themselves. When I went to school there were certain people; in fact the jewellers where I had been going
 since I was eight years of age (I'm still friendly with them now) I thought their station in life was higher than mine, which of course it was. They were jewellers, they were in business. They had money, we hadn't. I used to like to be with them, not bec
a
use I was a snob or other people were outcasts but when you're young you kind of get dressing nice and you go out for better dress, and I did think I was a bit better than them because I was educating myself a bit more than the ordinary. And we went out i
n their car on a Wednesday afternoon when it was their half day, which they had a car even then before 1918, and we thought we were it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 So you thought the shopkeepers were one group. What other groups do you remember?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 People who had better jobs.
 They would be tradesmen. And I remember somebody saying better off, oh they're alright, they are nice people at church, because I think my father said they worked in a solicitors office them two boys are very, very good. Two good young men, who was in my
 class at Sunday School, and that they would get on in the world, and eventually they did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 They became solicitors' clerks.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who did you think were the upper class group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think mostly shopkeepers. They kept to themselves. They seemed to be above 
the other people, because I suppose they was afraid that if they kept on par with the ordinary people they wouldn't get their money, which they had a tick shop running up a book and paying at the weekend. And if they came down to their own level they'd be
 left in the lurch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who did you think were the upper classes though, above the shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
I don't know. As you say, tradesmen might have been, because it was something to have a trade. There was apprentices at that time you know, bound for seve
n years and all that. And they came out of their time at 21. And the poor kind of kept to themselves. The politics which did come into it before the conservatives seemed to be the landed gentry and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Labour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  and the liberals was the poverty stricken people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now which class do you think you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And what sort of people belonged to the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The ordinary rank and file. We were clannish. People who wanted to help themselves. We were a kind of 
a union to ourselves we had our own society, and we kind of went out to help one another. If anything went wrong we were hurt. Even when their children got into scrapes, probably in the hands of the police, one was hurt and one tried to help soothe the mo
t
her or father, because we thought disgrace had been brought on to the home. And it very often was a disgrace to get into the hands of the police them days there was no such thing as a suspended sentence one went to the Industrial School, if they didn't se
nd the children to school. Salford Industrial School which I well remember, it only went down in about 1920.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And this was a sort of remand school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 If children didn't attend a school regular, there was a law where they had to be sent to Industrial
 School for part work and part schooling and they were very strictly superintended, under strict discipline, with a master in charge. And we use to feel for that and never look down upon them. And we, although we were the working class, we were educating 
ourselves. My father educated himself. And we were never snobbish, we didn't look down on anybody.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you ever remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. I don't think we were singled out to respect anybody more than the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you ever told to curtsey; touch your cap; or show respect in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We did to priests of the church. We used to touch our caps - we always wore caps then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about your sisters, did they have to curtsey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
They did. I've actually seen it even a few years ago, where the old style woman would curtsey as nuns were passing, or a priest, as they was saintly people and the respect was given to them. If I wanted to talk to anybody who wasn't altogeth
er up in the world, always stand aside if somebody was talking to them 'til their eye would catch mine. Never butt into a conversation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And this was mostly priests, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Or anybody else, who was well known, even today when anybody is taking part in a conversation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you ever taught to call anyone 'sir', or 'master', or 'madam'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about 'sir'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Only our teachers, they were called 'sir'. We respected our teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about 'master'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 But at work, I don't think even then, I can't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about 'madam'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. Mostly servants I would think would call people 'madam', but we were never trained to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways? Calling them 'sir' or 'madam'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. But my father was highly respected.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 In the district where you lived who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well there was the grocer that we dealt with. He put up for the Board of Guardians, and we thought he was 
something. He was on the Board of Guardians and a member of the church, and mother used to say "Oh, Mr. Rigby, he's quite a gentleman isn't he." We looked at him as quite gentleman and erect when he'd be walking in processions round the parish.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who did the shopkeepers associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
The clergy was men apart but they looked after their people. They paid regular visits to their homes. They was constantly concerned about what was happening in the home and 
they visited you to see how you were going on at home, see if you were in need of help or any charitable organisation and they'd put you on to the one my father was president of. We gave great respect when they entered the house. We again would never sit 
'til they came and sat down. We would offer a seat, a chair, to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You felt that the priests were the power did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes, they were ones who would lead. Who would give you help in difficulties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about the teachers then, did you feel they had any power?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The teachers they thought a lot of their pupils. They kept mostly to themselves as teachers. But they were power for good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about farmers, did you know any farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about employers? Who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Oh well, they had their own clubs and their own organisations and they stayed and passed amongst themselves. They had the Masonic clubs and they mixed with people they thought was in th
e money and who was out to make money, or where they could get on with. Some were kind of hated or despised as taking out the last what they could out of the workers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What sort of people would you say went to church? And what sort went to chapel? Tell me the different between the two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well in the church most of the poverty stricken people went to church, to the Roman Catholic Church. But to the Church of England most of the elite - the not exactly landed gentry, but the people who had the money. You'd see the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 foreman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  or the overlookers or the employers at Church of England, a kind of respectable gang, and then they'd be slave drivers on the Monday.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you always think the Protestants were just this type?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think so. And the other peopl
e too - the Anglicans. The Methodists would meet you at the door with a kind of handshake and their prayer book in the hand, but we never did. We'd go to church on a Sunday morning and there'd be a man at the door, he used to take what we'd give at the do
o
r. Probably a penny or tuppence; a three penny bit was well for the rich. It was the pennies and tuppences what built up our schools and churches. And that's how we went. But I think the others, without distinction, they had their own kind of little selec
t, the poor really didn't go to them unless they went to a ragged school or a mission.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 These were attached to the Protestant church - the ragged schools and the missions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes, mostly, or Methodist. And they were very good because there were s
oup kitchens in them days where people would go for help, and you'd find that most of the poor supported these in order to get help. There was Regent Ragged School connected to St. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Bartholomew
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  Church of England, run by two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Ridgeway}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
 brothers, who were mar
ine storekeepers. Very great work done. The Catholic priest and the minister Mr. Patrick were great friends to one another and they were both on the school board. And Catholics who had trouble with their girls and boys would sooner go to Mr. Patrick of Ch
urch of England, than their own priest, because he wasn't so severe, and the Church of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 England}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
 would go to Father Shearen because he wasn't too severe. And they got a lot done. And they used to go almost arm in arm up Oakfield Road. There was no prejudice at all then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who did you feel were the type of people who went to chapel, the Methodists?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They were kind of select. Nicely dressed. It was a kind of Sunday religion whereas ours was an every day religion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Where you lived, did all the people 
in the working class have the same standard of living, or would you say there were different groups? And can you tell me a different family in each?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They might be in different groups. I mean to say, we, although we was working class, were well fed. T
here was others where the father of the home wouldn't work, a ne'er do well, wouldn't work properly, and there was no labour exchanges only Poor Law. What they called the guardians, and they had a nickname the 'grubber' for the guardians, and they hated t
h
e guardians in them days. It was the last resort. And a person who went for assistance in those days, they wouldn't say oh you can come in and get it. And there was the two groups - there'd be the father who'd look after his job come what may, and there'd
 be a father who'd get up when he liked and so }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 impoverised}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
 the children, and not only the children but the poor wife who had to keep the children. Now she had to go and plead to the Board of Guardians for help and no help would be given without a visitor. A
nd the home would be looked. And I remember my mother saying she was in this home where the woman used to come and help us now and again do the washing, and the old }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 G}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 uardian came and I was talking to her and advising her on the children, because he wouldn'
t work her husband, and he'd gone out and they was having a drink of beer I think, or something like that. And there was a knock at the door and he said he was Mr. Nicholson from the Board of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 
G}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 uardians and the woman asked him in. He said he was a friend of
 the house, a friend of the woman, to my mother. He sniffed and then said "You've been drinking whisky." She got hold of the bottle and she said "Only saffron for the children - it's something for the children to rub them." And it wasn't. If he had caught
 
them drinking they would have been ostracised, knocked off, and told "No relief given to you. You must go into the workhouse with the children." And anything they'd do rather than go in the workhouse. It was the last stigma. You were really down and paupe
rised to go into the workhouse.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 But you felt there were different groups, you say there was just the people who wouldn't work and the people who would?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We felt on a little higher plain. I felt, even then, sorry because there was children in thei
r bare feet. We never went in bare feet, we were always supplied with clogs or later shoes, but this family were always in their bare feet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You didn't feel there were different groups among the working people themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. You see in the mill where my sisters worked they were very clannish. All clannish together, they kind of despised their }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 overlookers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
, foreman, because he was trying to get out more work for the employer than they could sometimes get out. But I think the poor on the whole kept definitely together, they did, they had to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you remember a distinction between certain types of craftsmen and labourers? Did you feel there was a big distinction there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. The craftsmen were snobs to the labourers. Yes. If they had a trade
, a craftsman or an engineer, well they'd been apprenticed to their job. You was only a labourer, what else did you expect. They expected more money, you was kind of serfdom, scrap heap, if you hadn't a trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were some families thought of as rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. Oh yes. In those days my mother used to tell me about the scuttlers. They was gangs who met together and used to go out with scarves round their necks, called mufflers, red and white scarves tied in a knot. And call them I key, very common, Ikey 
mob. And they'd go out chasing on a Friday evening after the wages, chasing the girls, and if they'd seen any boys with their girls they'd have them. They'd take the belts round their waists, the men, and fight with these belts. And that went on in differ
e
nt districts - the Adelphi district here. And people were afraid of them and would avoid them like they do today, and the districts where they would congregate. Because they were dangerous and anybody who came into their path could get it, left, right or 
c
entre. And that was the different types of gangs. And rough types. You'd have foul mouthed women, vulgarities at that time. They'd be shouting different things in the streets. The days when they used to hang clothes in the street to be airing and the old 
props to push up the line, and very often the clothes would be missing, somebody would've stole the clothes, and all that kind of business.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. Only the working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well they could. And people I suppose went out to get better positions and to be
 thought more of than another. For instance, you might get girls going on to the stage because they thought it was a bit higher. Or people thought it was a bit lower.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you remember anyone personally who went up in the world?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. Only our own 
local M.P., Joe Tool, who was a working class man who did strike out, work very hard, from being a labourer, a jack of all trades, to going on to the Manchester Guardian as a journalist. Being a salesman and eventually getting to the City Council and the 
youngest J.P., youngest councilor I think at 27 or 28 years of age, until he came here and took Salford in his stride in 1924 and won the election.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember anyone being described as a 'real lady' or a 'real gentleman' and why do you think it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
I don't exactly remember them. But I suppose it would be their mannerisms. The way they conducted themselves. My mother might say "She's a real lady and he's a thorough gentleman." And you would give them all the respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child and what did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well the policeman used to do their beat regularly round the streets. And we'd run into the house as soon as we seen him coming down the street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You were afraid of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your mother ever threaten you with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. "I'll tell the policeman." Big 6 ft. burly man, all powerful man, but little brains in them days because they got into the jobs because they was powerful not through educational methods.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you think he treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
With scorn. With contempt. He knew the district. He knew where rows were likely to brew and he used to look up to the bedrooms or the kitchens and stand near and wait. And if there was a row goin
g on people would very often run in and say come into the house. And he'd have to be invited in and there was probably pandemonium going on, a man breaking up the home, and all that kind of business. But in them days they was not looked on as a friend bec
a
use we were afraid. Playing football in the street "Oooh here's the policeman, or plain clothes, here's the D's, the 'tees, coming along." And we would scatter and we were afraid of them. The policeman would get hold of their football and put a knife into
 it and throw it back to them. They'd be big boys, say 11 or 12, and he would cut it up. They had that power. They could prosecute a child but now they have to go through their parents.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Is your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you see anything of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
On a Monday afternoon when he came the rent book would be put on the old fashioned drawers, and the rent, I can remember the first rent book. I've got it now 1907. 4/6 for rent, 1/- for key money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Key money, why key money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don
't know, the rent was 5/6. I don't know, I think they got people to clean the houses, and 1/- at that time key money, I could never make it out. And my mother paid it. He was very good, very chatty. He was only the agent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What did you feel about him though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
I kind of resented him. He was somebody we thought at first but at the same time we resented him. We must pay this rent to live for another week otherwise you'd be turned out of your home. And the rent must be there at all costs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now I remember you saying that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet. What did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Very often disquiet or sadness. Only hoping that I was able to bring some money in, able to work. I've seen towards the end of the week, my mother wh
en it comes to Friday managed to get the meal out, we were Catholics we didn't eat meat we had fish, either boiled fish with parsley sauce or fish and chips, and the last of the money had gone 'til Friday evening. And sometimes my mother would be sad and 
I'd feel with her. Sometimes inclined to cry. But she never broke down and the old fashioned purse would be empty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you remember your father being ill or out of work before he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. I can remember him being ill, not long, I think he'd hurt his foot. He was probably off work a week that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever have to go to the guardians or the parish or any charity or anything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think later my mother went to the Guardians. I think I can remember just before I was working and I think my father had died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did they treat her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh terrible. She used to come back heartbroken.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And how did she feel and how did you feel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Very humiliated and so would I. Yes, in those days they would question what had your daughters be
en giving you, and so embarrassing that they'd even phone to the work and ask, to make true that it was right that the girls had earned this much. And it would get round the overlookers that the Guardians had been on to them, you see, and it was a humilia
ting thing. And very often your mother would get nothing from the Guardians. And they were ordinary men with little or no education some of the Guardians, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 overseers,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872  and very often you'd have to go before a meeting of the Guardians, which met on a Frida
y morning. The overseers were the worst people - they used to bombast, and if they could bombast you or shout the hardest because you went in with a bundle of nerves, they won the day. Those days was torturing days and people said work if we can, rather t
han the 'grubber', rather than starvation, rather than the workhouse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you ever given lessons by one of your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No, not at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think about five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 When you first started what time of the morning did you go to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh, nine o'clock in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And what time did you come back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 'Til twelve o'clock. And then we went back at two o'clock 'til four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You went to afternoon school right from the beginning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. We came out at four o'clock, because the bigger ones came out at half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What kind of school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 A church school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 A day school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was it boys and girls mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No we were boys on our own, and girls on our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 We walked from home. About five minutes it would take us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well in the early times, starting for the first few weeks, my mother used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Where did you have your midday meal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Always at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What did you think of school? Did you like it, or did you dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No I didn't dislike it. I never didn't want to go. I was quite happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They were all right. Good teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life? Such as manners, tidiness, punctuality and ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes they always insisted on us being punctual and clean and tidy, and manners was first rate. They always enlarged on manners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about ways of speaking, did they have anything to say about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. There was no immediate part in the ways of speaking they didn't tell us anything about that. Left it to grow on us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What did they feel was the most important thing in life though, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well to tell the truth. Obedience.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Suppose you did something the teachers disapproved of, what would happen? How did they punish the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They'd punish. They'd have a cane, a l
ong cane, and you was brought out in front of the class and you got once or twice strokes with the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you know if the girls got the same as the boys? I know they weren't at your school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think they would. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And for what offences did you get punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 If we got anything wrong in the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you mean if you got the lessons wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes if you got the lessons wrong. Or if you came late, you'd get punished. Or if you did something out of school and it came to the not
ice of the teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Such as what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Probably giving a rise to somebody else and the parent came up to the school and complained about you. You'd very often be brought out and you might be caned or you might be just talked to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your parents show an interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. They were keen. They watched your movements.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did they ask you what you did at school; visit the school and meet the teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 My mother visited the school and talked to the teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. You might have one or two from different families. Say, probably a shop - we had one from a jewellers - and they were looked up as kind of a bit superior because they had a business. But more or less we were all the same type children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Oh yes. They would. The ones that had the shop, probably they were moneyed people, they favoured them a
 little bit and talked to them more than anybody else. But we all got the same kind of teaching and tuition and lessons. Nobody went short of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were they the only type that got singled out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes I should think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
I don't remember anything. Boys would club together themselves and talk in the school yard but we never went on to exploits or devilment. I can't remember anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were there any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well you always got the odd boy in the corner of the playground who wouldn't mix, Or the girl, and they had to be brought out into games. It was their own fault if they didn't take part - they were never left out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Was this an Infant School or was it an all age school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well starting as an Infant School in the early years 'til we got into a higher class and then we went into what we called the 'big boys' somewhere about ten or eleven. We mixed with the other people probably about nine 
years of age in the same school. It was Infant School and then the higher school in the next department - all one school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you still go home to midday meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What did you think of the second school? Did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. We we
re kind of afraid of the other boys that were getting older 'til about thirteen, because we were about ten just coming up the rung of the ladder and they were about to leave school. And they did throw their weight about, kind of superior to us, but we nev
er indulged in any fights.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What did you feel about the teachers in this school, the boys' school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Well there was nothing extraordinary about them. They were firm disciplined teachers. We treated them as gentlemen, said 'sir' always and had great 
respect for them even when we was coming down the street. One in particular really feared us. We would stand aside to let him pass, and he was a thorough good teacher and we liked him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about the discipline here in the boys' school. How were you punished here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you have girls in this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Still all boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Anything in particular emphasised as you got older in this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. You lived up to the same things. Tell the truth and obedience.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were there any gangs or groups in this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Would you have stayed longer if you had had the opportunity?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't think I could have done at this one, but looking back now I would h
ave liked to have done. Gone on and excelled, probably to a higher school or University, something like that. But of course University was out then. There was no open school it was all the landed gentry or doctors' sons or something like that. But I would
 have liked to go on at something and probably got a degree.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you attend any part-time education after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I went to evening classes after I left school and I took up shorthand and improved my writing a great deal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you have any regrets about your education, apart from wanting to go on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No regrets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes I do. I have benefited.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 While you were at school did you have a part-time job or any means of earning a little regular money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Now I should like to ask you about your first full time job. What was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I went along with mother to the juvenile bureau and they said "Oh yes. We've got a nice little job here it's junior clerk in the Bleache
rs Association. It's not bad and it's good pay 10/6 a week." I went along, it was only a few yards from the labour exchange, and my mother came with me. We interviewed the man and he said "Oh yes, he's just the type. He can start on Monday morning and it'
s 8/6 a week." My mother said "Oh no, it's 10/6 the lady said." He said "Oh dear me, we're not up to 2/-." She said "Oh no, but it's 10/6 he should get paid." So I started on the Monday morning at 8 o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Eight 'til ha
lf past five and I think we did 5 1/2 day week. Saturday morning 'til twelve and no Sunday. I liked that and I think I stayed there about eighteen months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you have holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you feel it was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. Now and again we got a bonus. A war bonus because the First World War was on then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 All of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What was it spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I'd get my pocket money. It was a shilling, and my own clothes was bought out of that. And then it was pooled with the rest of the money.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Very well. There was only about five in the office. A small office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you feel about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Kind of superior. Well I first started he was opening a letter every morning then he'd sign them and I used to file the letters. And I was keen on his signature, so keen that I tried to imitate it. I liked his handwriting and
 I had to be careful later on because he found out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you feel about him as a person though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Someone to be admired. He wasn't haughty. He was a cashier. He was the head cashier but he seemed all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you feel about the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 It was a job. Passable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes I liked it but one wanted for a change. To get out. It was kind of closed in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did the job alter your attitude to school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. I don't think it did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Can you tell me if you've done any jobs since the First World War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes I left my first job after about eighteen months and went into a Cotton Warehouse and I was in the dispatch room, dispatching the goods, attending to what customers wanted. Getting them ready.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you get this second job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
I think I went back on my own to the labour bureau and they found me this job. It was in the centre of the city and I thought it was more important to be working in the city, one kind of was looked up to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well in th
is second job, I used to sort out the parcels and the mail and dispatch them to wherever they were going. Or send the goods to their destiny. Or whatever the customer wanted, go to the different departments and get them for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And what hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 The same as before. 8 'til half past five, and twelve o'clock on a Saturday. No Sunday work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I don't think that came into it again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What were you paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 15/- or 17/-.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And did you feel this was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. I felt more happier and I think my pocket money went up to 2/-.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 It was always turned up to my mother. It was never interfered with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you get on with the people in this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Very well indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How did you feel about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 He was quite all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 And did you like the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. I liked the job. It was an improvement on the first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 How what other jobs have you done since the First World War? After 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well there was quite a variation of jobs I had. I can't remember very much in and out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What type as a whole were they though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They was mostly clerical.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you stay at any one a long time? What was your last job?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well my last job was at Dumms, which I retired in. Do you mean that one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I was there for about twenty years, and retired about two years ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What type of job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Cash clerk.
 I was costing and reckoning up the jobs of what the mechanics did and the customers came to pay and I costed up their jobs or probably sent out the invoices to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you like this job or would you have preferred another type of occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
No. I was very happy in this job. I became redundant, two years or eighteen months before actual retirement, because I'd gone into another department and didn't seem able to fit into the new department and I think they wanted to get rid of me in this new 
department.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you serve an apprenticeship or training period for any of your jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you belong to any trade union or professional organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. Unfortunately I didn't because we had no clerical union, much as I would liked to have been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you feel that employers and workers had the same interests or different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Some employers didn't have the interest in the work or the people. Employees didn't either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you feel there were divisions of interest among workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Yes. You get the division in employees. They didn't care so what they did as long as they got their wages at the weekend. We found that in clerical as well as the manual work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about the employers, how do you think their interests differed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
You'd get a phony employer, a manager who was out for his self interests, running his department his way, he always did, and sometimes doing injustice to the worker. You might be conscientious yourself, working very hard doing your returns in yo
ur work and the manager wouldn't be clever enough to see the returns or would know the depreciation of stock or anything like that. He wouldn't know anything about it. You get that kind of manager who has just jumped up from the floor and no education.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Now going back to 1918 some people say that in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers. Did you feel that or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think so. You'd get somebody apprenticed to a craft, engineers or turners, or draughtsmen
, or anything like that and the rest may be just ordinary labourers and there was a distinction. They were kind of above one another - whereas the labourer had to depend on getting a job anywhere he was put and the craftsmen would go out and define their 
terms what they wanted themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were they able to do that in 1918 do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I think they could do that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. I wouldn't say that it changed 
it to any different sphere to what it always has been. One mixed up with people a lot and felt a sense of responsibility. One can't be too conscientious in employment but I always was, honesty and all that kind of business. On the other hand, you found pe
ople grossly dishonest in works.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I'd like to ask you about your life at home after you left school. Did you continue to live at home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did starting full time work change your relationship you\rquote re your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. None whatever, it was just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 What about your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. There was no such change as snobbery or anything, or distinction in the home. It was just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No we continued as it has always been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you still go to Sunday School?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well we'd grown out of the sphere then, but we still went to church Sunday morning and Sunday evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you take an interest in politics in those days when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well yes. I swerved into politics and from being a Liberal, as Liberals had died the death we became }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 Labour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 . Although up to 1918 I wasn't eligible for the vote, not 'til I was 21 in 1923.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Why were you interested in Labour. Why did you think Labour was good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Well it was kind of for the working class movement and we thought we'd get a square deal. We thought it would be all honey, if you like.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Were you a member of a political party at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you take part in any political activity other than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No, only election time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 You did take part then, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
Oh yes. We'd canvas. Knock on the doors and ask them if they'd been to vote and work feverishly for the candidate to get in and be disappointed if he didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
You told me earlier something of how you spent your spare time. After you started full time work did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way or did you do different things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 I was always a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7950595\charrsid9511872 bookworm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 , always reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you go out in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 
I went to the theatres. I went to the local Palace Theatre here and seen the Variety. The old timers, Ella Shields, Florrie Ford and all the old troupers who made the theatre live.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Who did you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 With a friend. A young man the same age as me, we went to school together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you make any new friends after you started work, boys or girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. I just had the one friend and kind of kept to myself and never went out with a crowd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you ever bring friends to your home though, later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No, we didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did you have any special friends at this time, apart from this particular man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 No. I just went to this friend's house. He was a jeweler, I mentioned before. And we'd probably go away together later.
 But we never made anybody else friends.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 He used to come to your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Yes. He knew my people very well. My sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5701797 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 Did your parents expect to know where you were?
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid5701797 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12217962 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10246792\charrsid9511872 They did, yes. We usually told them where we were going and what tim
e we expected to be in. It was an exception if it was half past ten, because I used to be running home at half past ten because ten o'clock was the zero hour, we had to be in and I was absolutely panting. Probably half past ten because the theatre was goi
ng on later, there was several encores and we couldn't leave because it was so delightful.
\par }}